{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-abe607f7c4281b45", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# NouveauVoice: Generating Novel Pseudo Speakers for Voice Anonymization\narXiv: 2607.03985\nAuthors: Meiying Melissa Chen, Anastasia Kuznetsova, Zhenyu Wang, Zhiyao Duan\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n===\n# VoiceSculptor: Your Voice, Designed By You\narXiv: 2601.10629\nAuthors: Jingbin Hu, Huakang Chen, Linhan Ma, Dake Guo, Qirui Zhan, Wenhao Li, Haoyu Zhang, Kangxiang Xia, Ziyu Zhang, Wenjie Tian, Chengyou Wang, Jinrui Liang, Shuhan Guo, Zihang Yang, Bengu Wu, Binbin Zhang, Pengcheng Zhu, Pengyuan Xie, Chuan Xie, Qiang Zhang, Jie Liu, Lei Xie\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A comprehensive data processing pipeline is constructed for large-scale collection, filtering, multi-dimensional annotation, and human verification to provide high-quality supervision for natural-language-driven voice design.\n  2. A chain-of-thought-based fine-grained attribute modeling strategy is introduced to explicitly decompose natural language instructions into structured intermediate reasoning steps, enabling precise and interpretable control over multiple acoustic and stylistic attributes.\n  3. A stochastic attribute token dropout strategy is proposed during training to prevent over-reliance on explicit attribute tokens and encourage the model to infer acoustic characteristics directly from natural language instructions.\n  4. A joint cross-entropy training objective over both text and speech tokens is adopted to learn a unified latent space that tightly couples natural-language semantics with low-level acoustic realizations.\n  5. A retrieval-augmented generation mechanism is incorporated during inference to retrieve semantically relevant in-domain instruction examples, significantly enhancing the model's generalization and robustness to out-of-domain natural language instructions.\n  6. VoiceSculptor achieves open-source state-of-the-art performance on the InstructTTSEval-Zh benchmark and is fully open-sourced to advance reproducible instruction-controlled text-to-speech research.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/控制-NL描述, TTS/控制-指令合成", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e45974bb-b816-4fcf-a9b3-335d4c1c9cf1", "uuid": "6b995cd7-83a9-4080-afbe-ad01a8b9d292", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:56:23.522Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# NouveauVoice: Generating Novel Pseudo Speakers for Voice Anonymization\narXiv: 2607.03985\nAuthors: Meiying Melissa Chen, Anastasia Kuznetsova, Zhenyu Wang, Zhiyao Duan\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n===\n# VoiceSculptor: Your Voice, Designed By You\narXiv: 2601.10629\nAuthors: Jingbin Hu, Huakang Chen, Linhan Ma, Dake Guo, Qirui Zhan, Wenhao Li, Haoyu Zhang, Kangxiang Xia, Ziyu Zhang, Wenjie Tian, Chengyou Wang, Jinrui Liang, Shuhan Guo, Zihang Yang, Bengu Wu, Binbin Zhang, Pengcheng Zhu, Pengyuan Xie, Chuan Xie, Qiang Zhang, Jie Liu, Lei Xie\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A comprehensive data processing pipeline is constructed for large-scale collection, filtering, multi-dimensional annotation, and human verification to provide high-quality supervision for natural-language-driven voice design.\n  2. A chain-of-thought-based fine-grained attribute modeling strategy is introduced to explicitly decompose natural language instructions into structured intermediate reasoning steps, enabling precise and interpretable control over multiple acoustic and stylistic attributes.\n  3. A stochastic attribute token dropout strategy is proposed during training to prevent over-reliance on explicit attribute tokens and encourage the model to infer acoustic characteristics directly from natural language instructions.\n  4. A joint cross-entropy training objective over both text and speech tokens is adopted to learn a unified latent space that tightly couples natural-language semantics with low-level acoustic realizations.\n  5. A retrieval-augmented generation mechanism is incorporated during inference to retrieve semantically relevant in-domain instruction examples, significantly enhancing the model's generalization and robustness to out-of-domain natural language instructions.\n  6. VoiceSculptor achieves open-source state-of-the-art performance on the InstructTTSEval-Zh benchmark and is fully open-sourced to advance reproducible instruction-controlled text-to-speech research.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/控制-NL描述, TTS/控制-指令合成", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ad33c3d8b212fcf4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# SelfTTS: cross-speaker style transfer through explicit embedding disentanglement and self-refinement using self-augmentation\narXiv: 2603.22252\nAuthors: Lucas H. Ueda, João G. T. Lima, Pedro R. Corrêa, Flávio O. Simões, Mário U. Neto, Paula D. P. Costa\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A model utilizing MPCL loss to generate effective label-oriented clusters for both speaker and emotion embeddings without the need for complex batching pipelines\n  2. An explicit disentanglement framework using cosine similarity loss in conjunction with GRL to effectively remove overlapping information from embeddings, thereby enabling robust cross-speaker style transfer\n  3. The use of the model's own Voice Conversion capability for Self-Augmentation to improve the naturalness of synthesized speech\n  4. A comprehensive evaluation, including cross-corpus experiments, conducted using open datasets and publicly available code\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/控制-风格标签, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多说话人\n===\n# QuarkAudio Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20151\nAuthors: Chengwei Liu, Haoyin Yan, Shaofei Xue, Xiaotao Liang, Xiaofu Chen, Bin Gong, Zheng Xue, Gang Song\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present H-Codec, a unified discrete audio tokenizer that integrates self-supervised learning representations into the tokenization process via dual-stream (acoustic and semantic) quantization, achieving remarkable audio reconstruction quality at a low frame rate.\n  2. We introduce advanced H-Codec variants, including H-Codec-1.5 with a dynamic frame-rate mechanism for adaptive temporal resolution and H-Codec-2.0 extending the sampling rate to 48 kHz for higher fidelity.\n  3. We propose QuarkAudio, a unified decoder-only autoregressive language model framework that uses task-specific conditional information and special task tokens to distinguish and unify multiple audio processing and generation tasks within a single set of shared weights.\n  4. We extend unified audio generation to universal free-form audio editing guided by natural language instructions, covering both speech semantic editing and audio event editing.\n  5. We demonstrate that QuarkAudio achieves competitive or comparable high-fidelity generation performance against state-of-the-art task-specific or multi-task systems across speech restoration, target speaker extraction, speech separation, voice conversion, and language-queried audio source separation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-语音编辑, TTS/功能-多任务统一, 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e45974bb-b816-4fcf-a9b3-335d4c1c9cf1", "uuid": "8173a224-3e2b-47f5-a8a2-b9301a0ccdd6", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:56:23.995Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# SelfTTS: cross-speaker style transfer through explicit embedding disentanglement and self-refinement using self-augmentation\narXiv: 2603.22252\nAuthors: Lucas H. Ueda, João G. T. Lima, Pedro R. Corrêa, Flávio O. Simões, Mário U. Neto, Paula D. P. Costa\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A model utilizing MPCL loss to generate effective label-oriented clusters for both speaker and emotion embeddings without the need for complex batching pipelines\n  2. An explicit disentanglement framework using cosine similarity loss in conjunction with GRL to effectively remove overlapping information from embeddings, thereby enabling robust cross-speaker style transfer\n  3. The use of the model's own Voice Conversion capability for Self-Augmentation to improve the naturalness of synthesized speech\n  4. A comprehensive evaluation, including cross-corpus experiments, conducted using open datasets and publicly available code\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/控制-风格标签, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多说话人\n===\n# QuarkAudio Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20151\nAuthors: Chengwei Liu, Haoyin Yan, Shaofei Xue, Xiaotao Liang, Xiaofu Chen, Bin Gong, Zheng Xue, Gang Song\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present H-Codec, a unified discrete audio tokenizer that integrates self-supervised learning representations into the tokenization process via dual-stream (acoustic and semantic) quantization, achieving remarkable audio reconstruction quality at a low frame rate.\n  2. We introduce advanced H-Codec variants, including H-Codec-1.5 with a dynamic frame-rate mechanism for adaptive temporal resolution and H-Codec-2.0 extending the sampling rate to 48 kHz for higher fidelity.\n  3. We propose QuarkAudio, a unified decoder-only autoregressive language model framework that uses task-specific conditional information and special task tokens to distinguish and unify multiple audio processing and generation tasks within a single set of shared weights.\n  4. We extend unified audio generation to universal free-form audio editing guided by natural language instructions, covering both speech semantic editing and audio event editing.\n  5. We demonstrate that QuarkAudio achieves competitive or comparable high-fidelity generation performance against state-of-the-art task-specific or multi-task systems across speech restoration, target speaker extraction, speech separation, voice conversion, and language-queried audio source separation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-语音编辑, TTS/功能-多任务统一, 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a17ad68b794935db", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Make-A-Voice: Unified Voice Synthesis With Discrete Representation\narXiv: 2305.19269\nAuthors: Rongjie Huang, Chunlei Zhang, Yongqi Wang, Dongchao Yang, Luping Liu, Zhenhui Ye, Ziyue Jiang, Chao Weng, Zhou Zhao, Dong Yu\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose a unified voice synthesis framework called Make-A-Voice that utilizes a three-stage \"coarse-to-fine\" approach to model semantic meanings, acoustic conditions, and perceptual fidelity.\n  2. We enhance data scalability by leveraging self-supervised audio-only data for both the acoustic and generation stages without requiring annotations.\n  3. We achieve state-of-the-art results in style similarity and perceptual quality across three voice synthesis applications, demonstrating the framework's controllability and conditioning flexibility.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多任务统一, TTS/功能-多说话人\n===\n# Unifying Speech Recognition, Synthesis and Conversion with Autoregressive Transformers\narXiv: 2601.10770\nAuthors: Runyuan Cai, Yu Lin, Yiming Wang, Chunlin Fu, Xiaodong Zeng\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose GPA, a unified autoregressive LLM framework for TTS, ASR, and VC that enables instruction-driven task switching without architectural modifications.\n  2. We demonstrate that joint multi-task training across ASR, TTS, and VC enhances overall model performance by leveraging shared representations in a discrete latent space.\n  3. We show that the purely autoregressive architecture of GPA enables straightforward deployment, superior concurrency, and higher throughput compared to hybrid alternatives.\n  4. We introduce a family of GPA models, including a highly compact 0.3B-parameter variant explicitly designed for deployment in resource-constrained and edge environments.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, ASR, ASR/训练-监督", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e45974bb-b816-4fcf-a9b3-335d4c1c9cf1", "uuid": "4f3d550e-7236-4d1e-b642-915fca8ffd2d", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:56:24.459Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Make-A-Voice: Unified Voice Synthesis With Discrete Representation\narXiv: 2305.19269\nAuthors: Rongjie Huang, Chunlei Zhang, Yongqi Wang, Dongchao Yang, Luping Liu, Zhenhui Ye, Ziyue Jiang, Chao Weng, Zhou Zhao, Dong Yu\nYear: 2023 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose a unified voice synthesis framework called Make-A-Voice that utilizes a three-stage \"coarse-to-fine\" approach to model semantic meanings, acoustic conditions, and perceptual fidelity.\n  2. We enhance data scalability by leveraging self-supervised audio-only data for both the acoustic and generation stages without requiring annotations.\n  3. We achieve state-of-the-art results in style similarity and perceptual quality across three voice synthesis applications, demonstrating the framework's controllability and conditioning flexibility.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/控制-参考语音, TTS/功能-多任务统一, TTS/功能-多说话人\n===\n# Unifying Speech Recognition, Synthesis and Conversion with Autoregressive Transformers\narXiv: 2601.10770\nAuthors: Runyuan Cai, Yu Lin, Yiming Wang, Chunlin Fu, Xiaodong Zeng\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose GPA, a unified autoregressive LLM framework for TTS, ASR, and VC that enables instruction-driven task switching without architectural modifications.\n  2. We demonstrate that joint multi-task training across ASR, TTS, and VC enhances overall model performance by leveraging shared representations in a discrete latent space.\n  3. We show that the purely autoregressive architecture of GPA enables straightforward deployment, superior concurrency, and higher throughput compared to hybrid alternatives.\n  4. We introduce a family of GPA models, including a highly compact 0.3B-parameter variant explicitly designed for deployment in resource-constrained and edge environments.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, ASR, ASR/训练-监督", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
